    <text xml:space="preserve">
      <body>
         <div type="edition" xml:lang="ocm-Latn" rendition="class:83233 maturity:83211">
           <p><lb n="1"/>narīy· talāṅ· tauṅ·
		<lb n="2"/>jamalaṅ· Avīs·
		<lb n="3"/>sā vauḥ ka<choice><unclear>n</unclear><unclear>t</unclear></choice>anāy· <unclear>ño</unclear></p>
         </div>
         <div type="apparatus"/>
         <div type="translation" resp="part:argr">
 	         <p>From Ta Lang up to Jama Lang, all <supplied reason="explanation">village</supplied> have one piece of <foreign>katanāy/kananāy</foreign>.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>Our interpretation assumes that <foreign>talāṅ</foreign> and <foreign>jamalaṅ</foreign> are precursors of the toponyms Tà Làng and Xamơ (Samo) that designate places near the site of the inscription until this day. The word <foreign>tauṅ</foreign> has so far only been encountered in expressions of duration of time, but here seems to express extent of space. The reading and meaning of the penultimate word is uncertain, but we must be dealing with a noun countable with object classifier vauh, derived from a base <foreign>katāy</foreign> or <foreign>kanāy</foreign>. It seems that <foreign>ño</foreign> must be variant of the third-person pronoun that is <foreign>ñū</foreign> elsewhere in Old Cham (<bibl><ptr target="bib:Griffiths2025_01"/><citedRange unit="page">67-69</citedRange></bibl>).</p>
         </div>
        <div type="bibliography">
           <p>The inscription was tentatively deciphered, though not translated, in <bibl><ptr target="bib:Wittayarat2004_01"/></bibl>. It is re-edited here from photographs and after autopsy of the stone in March 2026.</p>
